defaultAbout usdefault&#xa0;
default1.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Centre for Crime and Justice Studies 
default(hereafter ‘the Centre’) 
defaultwas founded in 1931. We advance public understanding of crime, criminal justice and social harm. We are independent and non-partisan, though motivated by our values. We stand with those most vulnerable to social harm. We believe that the United Kingdom’s over reliance on policing, prosecution and punishment is socially harmful, economically wasteful, and prevents us from tackling the complex problems our society faces in a sustainable, socially just manner.
default&#xa0;
default1.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThrough our various events we bring people together to share ideas and develop solutions. In partnership with Oxford University Press and an independent international editorial board we publish the 
defaultBritish Journal of Criminology
default, one of the world’s top criminology journals. In partnership with Taylor and Francis and an 
defaultindependent 
defaulteditorial advisory board we publish 
defaultCriminal Justice Matters
default, a 
defaultquarterly magazine covering contemporary developments relating to political debate, policy and research. 
defaultOur annual publication
default 
defaultUK Justice Policy Review
default 
defaultreviews criminal justice and welfare policy across the four nations of the United Kingdom.
default 
defaultWe also produce a range of other 
defaultreports draw
defaulting
default on our own research as well as research by our partners and collaborators.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn July 
default2013 the Centre launched 
defaultJustice Matters: 
defaulta three year initiative 
defaultpromoting
default fresh thinking on downsizing the United Kingdom
default’s
default criminal justice systems and 
defaultthe development of
default 
defaultalternative policies and practices 
defaultthat are 
defaultproportionate response
defaults
default to the harms people experience.
